The State Labor and Commerce  Committee is hearing testimony on the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act.
Olson: We were told If you like your doctor, you can keep your doctor. If you like your health care plan, you can keep your health care plan
Lori Wing-Heier, Div. of Insurance: In 2013, people were shocked with the notices of cancellations.
Division of Insurance: We feel we impacted about 5,000 Alaskan and allowed them to stay out of an ACA plan.
Division of Insurance: We have to comply with the ACA. We are a small market. 28-29,000 people enrolled in the individual market.
Division of Insurance: There is not enough in the pool to spread the cost in the plans we have seen.
Division of Insurance: If we added in everyone who would enroll, the total number would be 30,000.
Division of Insurance: We are a small market, and there is nothing about the ACA that is going to change it.
Division of Insurance: There is not a way to spread the cost over this pool of people in a way that would make this affordable.
Div of Insurance: On the FFM, which Alaska is a part of, it’s $12,890 per enrollee, just to access the web site and process the application.
Division of Insurance The cost is astronomical for these exchanges.
Division of Insurance: In Alaska we only have 8 insurers. Some states have up to 40 insurers.
Division of Insurance: Premera and Moda are writing about 75 percent of the insurance plans.
Division of insurance does not set premium rates. The insurers file their  rates and the division approves or disapproves.
Division of Insurance: They cannot be excessive. They cannot be inadequate. They cannot unfairly discriminate.
Div of Insurance: There was significant adverse loss experience in 2014. There were some sick individuals who were in need of health care.
Division of Insurance: Insurers were paying out over $2.50 for claims for every dollar they were taking in.
Division of Insurance: Nothing in this act is affordable.
Division of Insurance: We are doing everything in our power to try and make it affordable.
Premera: Paid $7 million in claims from just 33 members.  We expect to lose $4 million in the market in 2014.
Premera : There’s a need to create a large enough pool to spread the costs.
Premera: Even if all of the individual market was in one pool the market in Alaska is too small to adequately spread the risk.
